Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that creates a 3D animation of the number "1" spinning around. The code includes embedded CSS and JavaScript, all within a single code block. You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see the animation.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>3D Spinning Number 1</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #282c34;
            perspective: 1000px;
        }

        .number {
            font-size: 100px;
            color: #61dafb;
            transform-style: preserve-3d;
            animation: spin 5s linear infinite;
        }

        @keyframes spin {
            from {
                transform: rotateY(0deg);
            }
            to {
                transform: rotateY(360deg);
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="number">1</div>

    <script>
        // You can add any additional JavaScript here if needed
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, VSCode, or any code editor).
3. Paste the code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `spinning_number.html`.
5. Open the saved file in a web browser.

You should see the number "1" spinning in 3D!

Sure! To make the number "1" appear thicker, we can use a combination of CSS properties such as `text-shadow` to create a 3D effect. Below is the updated HTML code with the thicker number "1" while keeping everything in a single file.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>3D Spinning Number 1</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #282c34;
            perspective: 1000px;
        }

        .number {
            font-size: 100px;
            color: #61dafb;
            text-shadow: 
                0 0 5px rgba(97, 218, 251, 0.5),
                0 0 10px rgba(97, 218, 251, 0.5),
                0 0 15px rgba(97, 218, 251, 0.5),
                0 0 20px rgba(97, 218, 251, 0.5);
            transform-style: preserve-3d;
            animation: spin 5s linear infinite;
        }

        @keyframes spin {
            from {
                transform: rotateY(0deg);
            }
            to {
                transform: rotateY(360deg);
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="number">1</div>

    <script>
        // You can add any additional JavaScript here if needed
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Open a text editor (like Notepad, VSCode, or any code editor).
3. Paste the code into the editor.
4. Save the file with a `.html` extension, for example, `thicker_spinning_number.html`.
5. Open the saved file in a web browser.

You should see a thicker, 3D spinning number "1"!
